articles.title: Cal Ripken Jr. is moving on, literally and figuratively
articles.description: The house that Cal built sits on 25 acres of land north of Baltimore, close enough for a short drive to the city but far enough to escape the rest of the world.

articles.title: 2 released from custody after NSA campus confrontation
articles.description: Two of the three people who were in a sports utility vehicle that was stopped and fired upon when it tried to enter the National Security Agency campus without authorization have been released, an FBI spokesman said Thursday.

articles.title: President's criticisms spark more protests at NFL games
articles.description: The owners of the Baltimore Ravens, the Super Bowl champion New England Patriots and other teams on Sunday joined a chorus of NFL executives criticizing President Donald Trump's suggestion that they fire players who kneel for the national anthem.

articles.title: Baltimore-bound USS Cyclops vanished 100 years ago. Its fate remains a mystery
articles.description: One hundred years ago Tuesday, the USS Cyclops was due to steam up the Chesapeake Bay and dock in Baltimore at what is now Port Covington. The ship still hasn’t shown up.

articles.title: Decorated Vietnam vet who rose to senior officer in Coast Guard Auxiliary, dies
articles.description: Robert J. Birrane Jr., a decorated Vietnam veteran who rose to become a senior Coast Guard Auxiliary officer, died May 30. “Bob emerged from his experience in Vietnam with a Bronze Star for heroism in combat," said Art Pine, a former reporter.

articles.title: NSA employee who worked on hacking tools at home pleads guilty to spy charge
articles.description: Federal prosecutors said they will seek an eight-year sentence for Nghia Hoang Pho, 67, of Ellicott City, Maryland, for willful detention of classified information.

articles.title: Fake Navy SEAL defrauded investment clients of over $1.4 million
articles.description: Edward I. Campbell boasted to his clients that he was a former Navy SEAL who had international business expertise and he could deliver huge returns on their investments. But federal investigators discovered another story.

articles.title: Maryland center offers shelter, services to oft-overlooked homeless female veterans
articles.description: The nonprofit Maryland Center for Veterans Education and Training, or MCVET, funded through the federal government, various organizations and private donations, has offered housing and a range of services for homeless male veterans since its launch in 1993. I…

articles.title: 10 African-Americans named Rhodes scholars, most ever
articles.description: The Rhodes Trust on Sunday announced the 32 men and women chosen for post-graduate studies at Oxford University in England. Among them: the first black woman to lead the Corps of Cadets at West Point; a wrestler at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology wh…

articles.title: Trump meets with families after Texas school shooting
articles.description: President Donald Trump began a trip to Texas on Thursday by meeting privately with families of some of the 10 people killed in a school shooting this month.

articles.title: Does the CIA have a new Aldrich Ames on its hands?
articles.description: For several years, federal investigators have been trying to determine whether a mole has been responsible for the imprisonment or deaths of the CIA's network of informants in China.
